column2: 1. Personal notes can go above the header row, you will just have to specify the number of rows to skip when uploading.
2. Employees must be uploaded or listed in the file before any of their dependents, but they do not need to be grouped together.  They can even be in separate files.
3. Employee rows must have the same Employee_SSN and Member_SSNs.
4. Dependent rows use the Employee_SSN for the Employee they go under, then their own SSN as the Member_SSN.
5. Corresponding Employees and Dependents must be under the same EIN (same company) - dependents assigned to a different EIN than their Employee will be skipped.
6. Multiple EINs are allowed in each file.
7. For Employee rows, months of coverage columns will be used in the covered individual section for this employee (see note 13 below).
8. For Dependent rows, only SSNs, EIN, Name, and Dependent fields will be used -- all other columns will be ignored.
9. SSNs do not have to be in the proper format (just need to be 7-9 digits).
10. Any number of lines can go above the header row.  When uploading, you will specify the number of rows to skip before the header.
11. The order of these columns do not matter, just make sure the header names match up with your file.

12. If you want to upload covered individuals (dependents) for an employee, make sure the CoveredIndividualInd column has a "1" in that employee.  Otherwise, it is not guaranteed, that the dependents will be uploaded.
13.  If CoveredIndividualInd is marked 1 (the checkbox above the covered individuals section) for an employee, that employee's information will be automatically inserted

into the first row of the covered individuals' section.  If this is not the case for this particular employee, you will have to go into the draft/edit form and manually delete it.  The auto-insert only
occurs when an employee is uploaded for the first time (does not happen if employee is overwritten [i.e. the Overwrite checkbox is on when uploading]).

14.  If CoveredIndividualInd is marked 0 (the checkbox above the covered individuals section - plan is not a self-insured plan) Part III-Covered Individuals of the 1095C is not completed (Columns BK - BX should be blank) and dependent information is not needed.
Side note about SSNs:
SSN's could have up to 2 leading zeroes.  If an SSN with leading zeroes is entered into excel without dashes, the leading zeroes will be taken off. (See Line 26 below for an example).
It is perfectly acceptable for this to happen.  When uploading, if an SSN has only 7 or 8 digits, leading zeroes will automatically be added.
Employee SSN; 1095C Box 2
